{"cursor":"8012","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox Former Country |native_name = Regne de Mallorca Reino de Mallorca\n Regnum Maioricae |conventional_long_name = Kingdom of Majorca |common_name\n= Majorca |continent = Europe |region = Iberian Peninsula |country = Spain\n|government_type = Monarchy |year_start = 1231 |year_end = 1715 |event_end =\nNueva Planta decrees |p1 = Crown of Aragon |flag_p1 = Estandarte de la Corona de\nAragon.svg |s1 = Enlightenment Spain |flag_s1 = Bandera de EspaÃ±a 1701-1760.svg\n|image_coat = Coat of Arms of the Kingdom of Majorca and the Balearic Islands\n(14th-20th Centuries).svg |image_map = Crown of majorca.jpg |image_map_caption =\nThe Kingdom of Majorca. |capital = Palma and Perpignan. |religion = Christianity\n(Roman Catholic), Islam, and Judaism. }} by James I of Aragon (1229)]]\n\nThe 'Kingdom of Majorca' (, ; ; ) was founded by James I of Aragon, also known\nas James The Conqueror. After the death of his first-born son Alfonso, a will\nwas written in 1262 which created the kingdom in order to cede it to his son\nJames. This disposition was maintained during successive versions of his will\nsuch that when James I died in 1276, the Crown of Aragon passed to his eldest\nson Peter, known as Peter III of Aragon or Peter the Great. The Kingdom of\nMajorca passed to James, who reigned under the name of James II of Majorca. The\nsame testament also established that the king of Majorca was a vassal to the\nking of Aragon. The title continued to be employed by the Aragonese and Spanish\nmonarchs until its dissolution by the 1715 Nueva Planta decrees.\n","linknr":225,"url":"Kingdom_of_Majorca","recorded":1374782362,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Kingdom_of_Majorca&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Kingdom_of_Majorca&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:Rec